title.narrative: 101 NEW-BORN, MATERNAL AND ADOLESCENT HEALTH

description.narrative: By 2022 government and partners have institutional capacity to ensure pregnant women, new-borns and adolescent girls, especially from marginalized groups have equitable availability, access, knowledge and demand for quality maternal, new-born and adolescent health care services both in community and health facility, in selected states, which contributes to Fast-Track The End Of Hiv/Aids, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Immunization Services As Part Of Primary Health Care, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Harnessing Power Of Business And Markets, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind, United Nations Working Together. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Business and Key Business Stakeholders demonstrate growing willingness, commitment and resource allocation for protecting and promoting child rights in policy and practice by 2022

description.narrative: During the COVID-19 pandemic, UNICEF has continued to sustain continuity of equitable and quality RMNCHA services, through system strengthening support for primary health care interventions for MNH, including health workforce resilience; and advocacy for accountability and focus on national newborn and maternal mortality and stillbirth goals.
